title: Dolphins' Jarvis Landry fined for unsportsmanlike conduct
text:
Dolphins' Jarvis Landry fined for unsportsmanlike conduct Jarvis Landry praises new coach Dan Campbell 
Dolphins wide receiver Jarvis Landry, who had a small skirmish with practice squad safety Ced Thompson during Wednesday's practice, appreciates Campbell's efforts in bringing out the team's 'competitiveness.' 

Dolphins wide receiver Jarvis Landry, who had a small skirmish with practice squad safety Ced Thompson during Wednesday's practice, appreciates Campbell's efforts in bringing out the team's 'competitiveness.' 
Jarvis Landry is $23,152 lighter in the wallet because of his unsportsmanlike conduct penalty Sunday. 
Jarvis Landry has been one of the Dolphins' most productive players this season, but he's going to be a little lighter in the wallet coming out the bye week. 
The wide receiver was fined $23,152 by the NFL on Friday for his argument with a game official during the fourth quarter of the Dolphins' 27-14 loss to the New York Jets this past Sunday in London. 
Landry was flagged for unsportsmanlike conduct as he argued that he was interfered with during an interception by Darrelle Revis in the end zone. (The fine of $23,152 is standard for a player's first such offense.) 
Landry has 28 catches for 270 yards this season, and his 69-yard punt return touchdown Week 1 in Washington delivered the Dolphins' lone win of the season. 
The team is off Sunday and returns to game action Oct. 18 at Tennessee.
